{
  "Climate and Weather Patterns": "气候和天气模式",
  "This lesson covers the fundamental measures of center used to analyze and summarize data sets. You'll learn how to calculate and apply the mean, median, and mode, and understand when each is most appropriate.": "这个课程涵盖了分析和总结数据集的中心的基本测量方法。 您将学会如何计算和应用平均值、 中位数和模式, 并了解何时最合适 。",
  "What is a freshwater ecosystem?": "什么是淡水生态系统?",
  "Freshwater ecosystems are defined by their low salt concentration (less than 1% salinity) and include bodies of water such as lakes, rivers, streams, ponds, and wetlands. They cover only about 3% of Earth's surface but support a disproportionately high percentage of global biodiversity.": "淡水生态系统的定义是低盐浓度(盐度低于1%),包括湖泊、河流、溪流、池塘和湿地等水体。 淡水生态系统仅覆盖地球表面的3%左右,但支撑着全球生物多样性比例过高。",
  "What is an estuary?": "什么是河口?",
  "Estuaries form where rivers meet the sea, creating brackish water with intermediate salinity. They are among the most productive ecosystems on Earth because nutrient-rich freshwater mixes with tidal saltwater, supporting diverse communities of fish, shellfish, birds, and other organisms.": "河流与海洋交汇,形成咸水和中间盐度,是地球上最具生产力的生态系统之一,因为富含营养的淡水与潮汐盐水混合,支持不同的鱼类、贝类、鸟类和其他生物群落。",
  "What is the photic zone of an aquatic ecosystem?": "水生生态系统的冰毒区是什么?",
  "The photic zone (also called the euphotic zone) extends from the water's surface down to approximately 200 meters in clear ocean water. This is where phytoplankton and algae perform photosynthesis, producing the majority of oxygen and organic matter that supports aquatic food webs.": "光伏区(亦称黄热带)从水面向下延伸至海洋清澈水域约200米处,植物浮游生物和藻类在此进行光合作用,产生大部分氧和有机物质,支撑水生食物网。",
  "What is the intertidal zone?": "潮间地带是什么?",
  "The intertidal zone is one of the most physically demanding marine habitats because organisms must withstand crashing waves, changing salinity, temperature fluctuations, and periodic exposure to air. Despite these challenges, intertidal zones support diverse communities of organisms adapted to these harsh conditions, including barnacles, mussels, sea stars, and various algae.": "潮间带是体力最强的海洋生境之一,因为生物必须抵御碰撞波浪、盐度变化、温度波动和定期接触空气。 尽管存在这些挑战,潮间带支持了适应这些严酷条件的不同生物群落,包括谷仓、贝类、海星和各种藻类。",
  "What is salinity and why does it matter in aquatic ecosystems?": "盐度在水生生态系统中有什么意义?",
  "Salinity is a key abiotic factor that determines the distribution of aquatic organisms. Freshwater has less than 0.5 parts per thousand (ppt) salt, while ocean water averages about 35 ppt. Organisms are adapted to specific salinity ranges, and changes in salinity can cause osmotic stress, making it a critical factor in defining aquatic habitats.": "淡水的盐分低于每千分之0.5,而海洋水的平均含量约为35 ppt。 生物体适应特定的盐度范围,盐度的变化可引起水生生物的压力,使其成为界定水生生境的一个关键因素。",
  "A limnologist studying a temperate lake in summer observes three distinct temperature layers: a warm upper epilimnion, a rapidly-changing thermocline in the middle, and a cold hypolimnion at the bottom. In autumn, surface water cools and the temperature layers break down, causing the entire lake to mix. What is this seasonal mixing process called, and why is it ecologically important?": "研究夏季温带湖的一位气候学家观察了三个不同的温度层:温暖的上层上层,中间迅速变化的热线,底部的低温层。 在秋天,地表水冷却和温度层分崩离析,导致整个湖融为一体。 这个季节性混合过程叫什么,为什么它具有生态重要性呢?",
  "Lake turnover occurs when surface water cools to the same density as bottom water, eliminating thermal stratification and allowing wind-driven mixing of the entire water column. This process is critical because it brings oxygen-depleted deep water to the surface for re-oxygenation and carries nutrient-rich bottom water upward, fueling phytoplankton growth. Lakes that experience this twice yearly (spring and fall) are called dimictic lakes.": "当地表水冷却到与底水相同的密度、消除热分层和允许风驱动混合整个水柱时,湖水的周转就会发生,这一过程至关重要,因为它将缺氧的深水带入地表,再氧化,并将富营养的底水带往上,为浮游植物生长提供燃料,每年经历两次(春季和秋季)的湖泊被称为糖尿病湖。",
  "Environmental scientists studying the Chesapeake Bay — the largest estuary in the United States — find that excessive nitrogen and phosphorus runoff from agriculture has caused massive algal blooms. These blooms block sunlight from reaching submerged aquatic vegetation and create oxygen-depleted 'dead zones' when the algae decompose. What is this process called?": "美国最大的河口切萨皮克湾(Chesapeake Bay)研究环境科学家发现,过度的氮和磷从农业中径流已导致大量藻类繁殖,这些开花阻止阳光到达水下水生植被,并在藻类分解时形成缺氧的“死区”。",
  "Eutrophication is the process by which excess nutrients (especially nitrogen and phosphorus) stimulate explosive algal growth in aquatic systems. When these algal blooms die, decomposing bacteria consume large amounts of dissolved oxygen, creating hypoxic (low oxygen) or anoxic (no oxygen) zones where most marine life cannot survive. The Chesapeake Bay has experienced significant dead zones due to agricultural runoff, leading to major restoration efforts.": "富营养化是过度养分(特别是氮和磷)刺激水生系统爆炸性藻类生长的过程,当藻类大量繁殖死亡时,分解的细菌消耗大量溶解氧,形成缺氧(低氧)或厌氧(无氧)区,大多数海洋生物无法生存。 切萨皮克湾因农业径流而经历了大量死亡区,导致重大恢复努力。",
  "A freshwater ecologist studies a river system from its narrow, shaded headwaters in the mountains to where it becomes wide and deep in the lowland floodplain. She observes that the types of organisms, energy sources, and nutrient processing change systematically. In the headwaters, the ecosystem relies heavily on leaf litter falling from overhanging trees. In the wide lower reaches, phytoplankton produce most of the organic matter. What is this pattern called?": "淡水生态学家研究一种河流系统,从山区狭小的、阴暗的头水到低地洪泛地的广度和深处。她指出,生物、能源以及营养加工的种类有系统变化。在头水中,生态系统严重依赖从悬浮树上掉落的叶子。在大面积的低处,浮游植物产生大部分有机物质。这种模式叫什么?",
  "The River Continuum Concept (RCC), proposed by Vannote et al. in 1980, describes how physical conditions change along a river's length and how biological communities respond. Headwater streams (orders 1–3) are heterotrophic, depending on allochthonous (external) organic inputs like leaf litter. Mid-reaches (orders 4–6) have the highest biodiversity and balanced energy sources. Large rivers (orders 7+) are dominated by fine particulate organic matter and phytoplankton production.": "1980年Vannote等人提出的环流河概念(RCC ) , 描述了河流长度的物理条件变化以及生物群落的应对方式。 头水流(1-3级)是血化的,取决于叶子等异地(外部)有机投入。 中层(4-6级)拥有最高的生物多样性和平衡能源来源。 大河(7+级)以细微微有机物和浮游植物生产为主。",
  "Every summer, a massive hypoxic zone forms in the Gulf of Mexico near the Mississippi River delta. This dead zone — sometimes exceeding 20,000 square kilometers — results from agricultural fertilizer runoff carried by the Mississippi River from farms across the Midwest. Algal blooms fueled by excess nutrients die and sink, and their decomposition by bacteria consumes dissolved oxygen. How does this dead zone affect aquatic organisms, and what is the ultimate cause?": "每年夏天,密西西比河三角洲附近的墨西哥湾都形成一个巨大的缺氧区,这一死区有时超过20,000平方公里,其原因是密西西比河从中西部的农场中流失农业化肥,海藻因过多的养分而死亡和沉没,细菌的分解消耗了溶解的氧气。 这个死区如何影响水生生物,最终原因是什么?",
  "The Gulf of Mexico dead zone is one of the largest examples of human-caused eutrophication. Nitrogen and phosphorus fertilizers from the 1.2-million-square-mile Mississippi River watershed wash into the Gulf, triggering massive algal blooms. When these blooms die and decompose, bacterial respiration depletes bottom-water dissolved oxygen below 2 mg/L (hypoxia), making it uninhabitable for most marine life. Addressing this requires reducing fertilizer use and improving agricultural practices across much of the central United States.": "墨西哥湾死区是人类导致富营养化的最大例子之一,密西西比河120万平方英里流域的氮和磷肥被冲入海湾,引发了大规模的藻类繁殖,当这些盛开和分解时,细菌再生会耗尽二毫克/升以下的底层溶解氧(天花),使大部分海洋生物无法居住,为此需要减少肥料的使用,改善美国中部大部分地区的农业做法。",
  "A coastal community drains and fills a large salt marsh to build a housing development. The following hurricane season, the community experiences catastrophic flooding far worse than historical records predict. Neighboring communities with intact salt marshes suffer significantly less flood damage despite receiving the same storm surge. What ecosystem service did the destroyed salt marsh provide?": "一个沿海社区排水排水,填满了巨大的盐沼以建造住房开发。 在随后的飓风季节,社区遭受的灾难性洪灾比历史记录预测的要糟糕得多。 附近带完好的盐沼的社区尽管遭受同样的风暴潮,但遭受的洪水破坏却要少得多。 被摧毁的盐沼提供了什么生态系统服务?",
  "Wetlands provide critical flood protection by absorbing excess water during storms. Coastal salt marshes specifically reduce storm surge height and energy by creating friction that slows water movement. Studies estimate that every acre of wetland can store 1–1.5 million gallons of floodwater. The loss of over 50% of the world's wetlands due to development has increased flood risks and costs worldwide.": "湿地通过在风暴中吸收多余的水来提供至关重要的防洪保护。 沿海盐沼特别通过制造减缓水流移动的摩擦来降低风暴潮的高度和能量。 研究估计,每个湿地的每英亩土地都能储存100万至150万加仑的洪水。 发展导致世界湿地损失超过50 % , 增加了全世界的洪水风险和成本。",
  "Researchers comparing coastal regions in Southeast Asia after the 2004 Indian Ocean tsunami found that villages behind intact mangrove forests suffered significantly less damage and fewer casualties than villages where mangroves had been cleared for shrimp aquaculture. The mangrove roots also trap sediment and their submerged root systems serve as nurseries for juvenile fish. What type of aquatic ecosystem are mangrove forests classified as?": "在2004年印度洋海啸之后,东南亚沿海地区的研究人员比较了2004年印度洋海啸之后发现,完好的红树林后面的村庄遭受的破坏和伤亡远远少于红树林被清理用于养虾养殖的村庄,红树林根部还把沉积物及其下沉根系作为幼鱼的苗圃,红树林被归类为哪类水生生态系统?",
  "Mangrove forests are coastal wetland ecosystems found in tropical and subtropical intertidal zones. Their complex root systems dissipate wave energy (reducing storm surge by up to 66%), trap sediments to build coastlines, and create sheltered nursery habitat for commercially important fish and crustaceans. Mangroves also sequester carbon at rates 3–5 times higher than terrestrial forests. Despite their value, over 35% of the world's mangroves have been lost since the 1980s.": "红树林是热带和亚热带潮间带的沿海湿地生态系统。 其复杂的根系统消散了波浪能量(风暴潮减少高达66% ) , 困住沉积物以建造海岸线,并为商业上重要的鱼类和甲壳类动物建立栖息地。 红树林还以比陆地森林高3-5倍的速率封存碳。 尽管其价值很高,但自1980年代以来,超过35 % 的世界红树林已经消失。"
}